         <abstract>
            <p>There is concern about soil compaction caused by agricultural equipment. The loads applied to soil by tractors, combines, and machines for transporting supplies and commodities are sufficient to significantly increase the bulk density of soil and to reduce crop production. The change in bulk density, cone index, and surface elevation caused by a combine when harvesting corn were measured. The combine depressed the soil surface from 1 to 4 cm depending upon previous tillage. Smaller and lighter machines, lower ground pressures, appropriate tillage, and control of equipment traffic are proposed as ways to reduce soil compaction and minimize its effect on crop production.</p>
         </abstract>
